solution: ```class Solution {
public:
    int removePalindromeSub(string s) {
        if (s.empty()) return 0;
        int l = 0, r = s.size() - 1;
        while (l < r) {
            if (s[l] != s[r]) return 2;
            ++l; --r;
        }
        return 1;
    }
};```
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(n)
space complexity: O(1)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: The string contains only 'a' and 'b', so any subsequence is either all 'a's or all 'b's. If the whole string is a palindrome, one step suffices. Otherwise, we can always remove all 'a's in one step (they form a palindromic subsequence) and all 'b's in the next step, totaling two steps.

